Definition 2.1. An idempotent closure operator $\overline{(\,\,)}$ on effective equivalence relations consists in giving for every effective equivalence relation $\xymatrix{S\ar[r]^{s}&X\times X}$ another effective equivalence relation $\xymatrix{\overline{S}\ar[r]^{\overline{s}}&X\times X}$ called the closure of $S$ in $X\times X$. This assignment has to satisfy the following properties, where $S$ and $T$ are effective equivalence relations on $X$, $\xymatrix{Y\ar[r]^{f}&X}$ is an arrow in $\mathcal{L}$ and $f^{-1}(S)$ is the inverse image of $S$ along $f$: 1. $S\subseteq\overline{S}$ 2. $S\subseteq T$ implies $\overline{S}\subseteq\overline{T}$ 3. $\overline{f^{-1}(S)}\subseteq f^{-1}(\overline{S})$ 4. $\overline{\overline{S}}=\overline{S}$
Definition 3.1. [15] Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an exact category, and let $\mathcal{L}$ be an epireflective subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$. One calls $\mathcal{L}$ a Birkhoff subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ when it is closed under regular quotients in $\mathcal{C}$: if $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ is a regular epimorphism with $X$ in $\mathcal{L}$, then $Y$ belongs to $\mathcal{L}$ as well.
Definition 3.4. A Birkhoff closure operator on effective equivalence relations $\overline{(\,\,)}$ is an effective closure operator satisfying the following additional property $(6)$: for any regular epi $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ and any equivalence relation $S\rightarrow X\times X$ one has that $(6)\qquad\overline{f(S)}=f(\overline{S}).$
Definition 3.2. An exact category $\mathcal{C}$ is a Goursat category [9] when any pair of equivalence relations $R$, $S$ on the same object $X$ in $\mathcal{C}$ satisfies the condition $R\circ S\circ R=S\circ R\circ S,$ where the symbol $\circ$ denotes here the usual relational composition in a regular category [2].
Definition 2.2. An idempotent closure operator on effective equivalence relations will be called an effective closure operator (on effective equivalence relations) if it also satisfies the following axiom: $(5)$ for any regular epimorphism $\xymatrix{Y\ar[r]^{f}&X}$ one has that $\overline{f^{-1}(S)}=f^{-1}(\overline{S}).$
Definition 1.1. Let $f:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{V}\mathbf{Cat}$. 1. The morphism $f$ is $\mathrm{homotopy\ essentially\ surjective}$ if the induced functor $[f]_{\mathcal{V}}:[\mathcal{A}]_{\mathcal{V}}\rightarrow[\mathcal{B}]_{% \mathcal{V}}$ is essentially surjective. 2. The morphism $f$ is a $\mathrm{DK-\ equivalence}$ if it is homotopy essentially surjective and locally in $\mathfrak{W}$. 3. The morphism $f$ is a $\mathrm{DK-\ fibration}$ if it satisfies the following two conditions. (a) $f$ is locally in $\mathfrak{Fib}$. (b) For any $x\in\mathcal{A}$, and any isomorphism $v:[f]_{\mathcal{V}}(x)\rightarrow y^{\prime}$ in $[\mathcal{B}]_{\mathcal{V}}$, there exists an isomorphism $u:x\rightarrow y$ in $[\mathcal{A}]_{\mathcal{V}}$ such that $[f]_{\mathcal{V}}(u)=v$. That is, if $[f]_{\mathcal{V}}$ is an isofibration.
Definition 4.1. A monoidal graph $(A,V,d_{0},d_{1})$ consists of a set $V$ of vertices, and a set $A$ of arcs and two functions $d_{0},d_{1}:A\longrightarrow\ V^{*}$ ($V^{*}$ the free monoid on $V$). A morphism of monoidal graphs $\phi=(\phi_{0},\phi_{1})$ from $(A,Y,d_{0},d_{1})$ to $(B,W,d_{0},d_{1})$ consists of two functions $\phi_{1}:A\to B$ and $\phi_{0}:V\to W$ such that $\phi_{0}d_{0}=d_{0}\phi_{1},\phi_{0}d_{1}=d_{1}\phi_{1}$. We denote the category (actually a presheaf category) of monoidal graphs as $MonGraph$. There is an obvious notion then of a monoidal diagram in a monoidal category since any monoidal category has an underlying monoidal graph.
Definition 2.1. A commutative separable algebra [1] in a symmetric monoidal category is an object $A\text{ equipped with four arrows}$ $!:I\longrightarrow A,\>\ \nabla:A\otimes A\longrightarrow A,\>\emph{\text{% \textexclamdown}}:A\longrightarrow I,\>\Delta:A\longrightarrow A\otimes A$ such that $(A,\triangledown,!)$ forms a commutative monoid, $(A,\vartriangle,\emph{\text{\textexclamdown}})$ forms a cocommutative comonoid, and the following three axioms hold $(1_{A}\otimes\nabla)(\Delta\otimes 1_{A})=\Delta\nabla=(\nabla\otimes 1_{A})(1% _{A}\otimes\Delta),$ $\nabla\Delta=1_{A}.$
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathbf{E}$ be a category with finite colimits, regarded as a monoidal category with sum as tensor. A cocone of a monoidal diagram $D$ to an object $X$ is a family of arrows $(q_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow X)\quad(A_{i}\text{ objects of the diagram $D$)}$ such that for any arrow $f:A_{i_{1}}+A_{i_{2}}+\cdots+A_{i_{m}}\to A_{j_{1}}+A_{j_{1}}+\cdots+ A_{j_{n}}$ in the diagram $(q_{j_{1}}|q_{j_{2}}|q_{j_{n}}|\cdots|q_{i_{1}})\cdot f=(q_{i_{1}}|q_{i_{2}}|q% _{i_{3}}\cdots|q_{i_{m}}).$ A colimit of monoidal diagram $D$ is an object $C$ with a cocone $q$ from $D$ which is univeral; that is, any cocone to an object $X$ factors uniquely through $q$.
Definition 1.13. Let $A$ be in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$, $f$ be an element of $A$ and $M$ an $A$-module. The multiplication by $f$ in $M$, denoted $\tau_{f}$ is defined by the following commutative diagram $\xymatrix{M\otimes_{A}A\otimes k\ar[r]^{Id_{M}\otimes f}\ar[d]_{r_{M}\otimes Id% _{k}}&M\otimes_{A}A\ar[d]^{r_{M}}\inner@par M\otimes k\ar[r]_{\tau_{f}}&M}$ In particular, when $M=A$, $\tau_{f}=\varphi(f)$ where $\varphi$ is the adjunction morphism defined in the preliminaries.
Definition 2.12. Let $A$ be a commutative monoid $\triangleright$ An isomorphism between two elements $f\in A_{k},\;g\in A_{k^{\prime}}$ is an isomorphism from $k$ to $k^{\prime}$ equalizing the two elements. $\triangleright$ Let $f$ be an element of $A$, the ideal generated by $f$ is denoted $(f)$.
Definition 1.5. Let $X$ be in $\mathcal{C}$ and $F=(f_{i})_{i\in I}$ be a family of elements of $X$. Let $sub_{F}X$ denote the full subcategory of $sub(X)$ whose objects are subobjects $Y$ of $X$ containing the family $F$. The object generated by $F$ is $X_{F}:=Lim_{sub_{F}X}Y$
Definition 2.1. Let $A$ be in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ i. Let $\mathcal{B}A$ denote the $\mathcal{C}$-category consisting of one object $*$ and an object of morphisms $\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}A}(*,*):=A\in\mathcal{C}$. ii. Let $Pr(\mathcal{B}A)$ denote the $\mathcal{C}$-category of $\mathcal{C}$-presheaves i.e. of $\mathcal{C}$-functors from $\mathcal{B}A$ to $\mathcal{C}$. iii. The Yoneda $\mathcal{C}$-functor consists of the $\mathcal{C}$-functor $*\rightarrow h_{*}$ which is defined on objects by $h_{*}(*)=A$ and on morphisms by the adjoint $h_{*}:A\rightarrow\underline{End}_{\mathcal{C}}(A)$ of $m_{A}$.
Definition 4.2. i. Let $\mathcal{B}$ be a $\mathcal{C}-category$, $\mathcal{K}$ a small $\mathcal{C}$-category, and $F:\mathcal{K}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ and $G:\mathcal{K}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ two $\mathcal{C}$-functors. Then, if the functor $\mathcal{B}^{op}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$: $B\rightarrow\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}^{\mathcal{K}}}(F,\underline{Hom}_{% \mathcal{B}}(B,G-))$ is represented by an object $lim_{F}(G)$, $G$ has a $\mathcal{C}-limit$ indexed by $F$. ii. Let $\mathcal{B}$ be a $\mathcal{C}-category$, $\mathcal{K}$ a small $\mathcal{C}$-category, and $F:\mathcal{K}^{op}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ and $G:\mathcal{K}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ two C-functors. Then, if the functor $\mathcal{B}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$: $B\rightarrow\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}^{\mathcal{K}^{op}}}(F,\underline{Hom}% _{\mathcal{B}}(G-,B))$ is represented by an object $colim_{F}(G)$, $G$ has a $C-colimit$ indexed by $F$. iii. A $\mathcal{C}-category$ is finite if and only if its collection of objects is a finite set and for each couple of objects $(X,Y)$, the object $\underline{Hom}(X,Y)$ is finitely presented in $\mathcal{C}$. iv. A $\mathcal{C}-limit$ is finite if and only if it is indexed by a functor $F:\mathcal{K}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}_{0}$ from a finite $\mathcal{C}-category$ $\mathcal{K}$ to the generating subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ consisting of finitely presented objects.
Definition 1.1. Let $u:X\rightarrow Y$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{C}$. $\triangleright$ Let $\mathcal{C}_{Y}$ denote the full sub-category of $\mathcal{C}/Y$ consisting of objects $Z$ such that the morphism $Z\rightarrow Y$ is a monomorphism. A subobject of $Y$ is an isomorphism class of objects in $\mathcal{C}_{Y}$. The category of subobjects of $Y$ will be denoted $sub(Y)$. $\triangleright$ A subobject $Z$ of $Y$ contains the image of $u$ if $u$ factors throught the inclusion $Z\hookrightarrow Y$. We denote by $sub_{u}Y$ the category whose objects are subobjects of $Y$ containing the image of $u$ and whose morphisms are monomorphisms. $\triangleright$ The image of $u$, denoted $Im(u)$ is $Im(u):=Lim_{sub_{u}Y}Z$. $\triangleright$ Let $|u|$ denote the object $|u|:=Coker(\xymatrix{X\times_{Y}X\ar@<1ex>[r]\ar@<-1ex>[r]&X})$.
Definition 3.4. Let $A$ be a commutative monoid in $\mathcal{C}$ and $F$ be a Zariski open subobject of $Spec(A)$. There exists a family of affine Zariski open subobjects $(Spec(B_{i}))_{i\in I}$ of $Spec(A)$ such that $F$ is the image of $\coprod_{i\in I}Spec(B_{i})\rightarrow Spec(A)$. The Gabriel filter associated to $F$ is $G_{F}:=\cap_{i\in I}G_{B_{i}}$.
Definition 1.9. Let $A$ be a commutative monoid and $M$ be an $A$-module. A sub-$A$-module of $M$ is a subobject of $M$ in the category $A-mod$. An ideal of $A$ is a sub-$A$-module of $A$.
Definition 2.4. A localization of $A-mod$ consists of a full reflexive (saturated) sub-$\mathcal{C}$-category of $A-mod$ such that the left adjoint of the inclusion $\mathcal{C}$-functor is left $\mathcal{C}$-exact.
Definition 1.6. Let $X$ be in $\mathcal{C}$ and $F=(f_{i})_{i\in I}$ be a family of elements of $X$. The presheaf associated to $F$, denoted $F^{\prime}$, is defined by $F^{\prime}:k\rightarrow F(k):=\{f\in X_{k}\;st\;\exists\;h:k\rightarrow k^{% \prime}\;and\;g\in F\cap C_{k^{\prime}}\;st\;f=g\circ h\}$
Definition 2.2. (cf [BQ] for general definition) A Grothendieck’s $\mathcal{C}$-topology on $\mathcal{B}A$ consists of a set $J$ of ideals of $A$ such that: i. $A\in J$ ii. $\forall q\in J$, $\forall k\in\mathcal{C}_{0}$ and $\forall f\in A_{k}$, $f^{-1}(q)=(q^{k}\times_{A^{k}}A)\in J$. iii. Let $q,r$ be two ideals of $A$, $q\in J$. If $\forall f:k\rightarrow q,\;k\in\mathcal{C}_{0}$ the ideal $f^{-1}(r)$ is in $J$, then so is $r$. Where $q^{k}=\underline{Hom}(k,q)$ and $A^{k}=\underline{Hom}(k,A)$ are expoential objects.This topology will be called a Gabriel filter. In $ii$ the morphism from $A$ to $\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(k,A)$ is the adjoint of the morphism $\varphi(f):(A\otimes k)\rightarrow A$.
Definition 4.1. i. A $\mathcal{C}-category$ $\mathcal{B}$ consists of a collection of objects $ob(\mathcal{B})$, for any two objects $(X,Y)$, of an object $\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}(X,Y)\in\mathcal{C}$ and of a composition law: $M_{X,Y,Z}:\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}(Y,Z)\otimes\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{B% }}(X,Y)\rightarrow\underline{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}(X,Z)$ such that the appropriate commutative diagrams commute. ii. A $\mathcal{C}-functor$ $F:\mathcal{B}\rightarrow B^{\prime}$ consists of, for each object $X$ in $B$, an object $F(X)$ in $B^{\prime}$, and for each couple of objects $(X,Y)$, a morphism: $\xymatrix{\underline{Hom}_{B}(X,Y)\ar[r]^{F_{X,Y}}&\underline{Hom}_{B^{\prime}% }(X,Y)}$ such that the appropriate diagrams commute. iii. An equivalence of $\mathcal{C}-category$ consist of a $\mathcal{C}-functor$ $\mathcal{C}$-fully faithfull such that its underlying functor is essentially surjective.
Definition 1.16. Let $A$ be in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ and $S$ be a multiplicative part of $A_{0}$. A localization of $A$ along $S$ is a couple $(S^{-1}A,w_{S})$, where $w_{S}:A\rightarrow S^{-1}A\in Comm(\mathcal{C})$, satisfying the following properties: i. The image of the elements of $S$ are invertible, ie $(w_{S})_{0}(S)\subset(S^{-1}A)_{0}^{*}$. ii. Any morphism verifying $i$ factors through $w_{S}$. More precisely, $\forall\xymatrix{A\ar[r]^{u}&B}\in Comm(\mathcal{C}),\;if\;u_{0}(S)\subset B_{% 0}^{*}$ then $\exists!\;v$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{A\ar[rr]^{u}\ar[rd]_{w_{S}}&&B\inner@par&S^{-1}A\ar[ru]_{v}&}$ If $S=<\{f\}>$ is the multiplicative part generated by one element $f$, $A_{f}$ will refer to $S^{-1}A$ and $w$ to $w_{S}$.
Definition 2.16. Let $A$ be a commutative monoid and $q$ be an ideal of $A$. $\triangleright$ The Gabriel filter $G_{q}$ is the smallest Gabriel filter of $A$ containing $q$ in the poset $GabA$. A Gabriel filter generated by one ideal in this sense will be called a primitive Gabriel filter. $\triangleright$ The Gabriel filter $G^{q}$ is defined by $G^{q}=\cap_{f\in q}G_{f}$ in the poset $GabA$. A Gabriel filter generated by one ideal in this sense will be called a locally primitive Gabriel filter.
Definition 1.11. Let $\xymatrix{A\ar[r]^{u}&B}$ be a morphism of commutative monoids and $q$ be an ideal of $A$. The image of the ideal $q$ in $B$, denoted $qB$, is the image of the morphism $q\otimes_{A}B\rightarrow B$ in $B-mod$.
Definition 2.10. Let $A$ be a commutative monoid $\triangleright$ Let $q,q^{\prime}$ be two ideals of $A$. The product $q.q^{\prime}$ is the image of the morphism $q\otimes q^{\prime}\rightarrow A$. $\triangleright$ An ideal $p$ of $A$ is prime if for all $q,q^{\prime}$ sucht that $q.q^{\prime}\subset p$, $q\subset p$ or $q^{\prime}\subset p$. $\triangleright$ A set $G$ of ideal of $A$ is filtered if for all $q\subset q^{\prime}$, $q\in G\Rightarrow q^{\prime}\in G$. $\triangleright$ A set of ideals of $A$ is commutative if it is closed under product of ideals. $\triangleright$ A set of ideals $G$ is quasi-compact if, for any ideal $q$ in $G$ isomorphic to a filtered colimit $colim_{i\in\mathcal{I}}q_{i}$, there exists $i$ such that $q_{i}$ is in $G$.
Definition 3.12. The Zariski topological space associated to $X:=spec(A)$, denoted $Lp(A)$ is the topological space whose points are prime ideals of $A$ and in which a closed subset is the set of prime ideals contained in a locally primite Gabriel filter.
Definition 1.23. (cf [TV]) i. A morphism $A\rightarrow B$ in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ is $\mathcal{C}$-flat if the functor $-\otimes_{A}B$ commutes with finite enriched limits (cf definition 4.2 in appendix). ii. A morphism $A\rightarrow B$ in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ is finitely presented if $B$ is finitely presented in $A-alg$. iii. A morphism $A\rightarrow B$ in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ is a formal Zariski open morphism if it is both a $\mathcal{C}$-flat morphism and an epimorphism. iv. A morphism $A\rightarrow B$ in $Comm(\mathcal{C})$ is a Zariski open morphism iff it is a finitely presented formal Zariski open morphism. In this case, $Spec(B)$ will be called a Zariski open subobject of $Spec(A)$.
Definition 3.1. Let $Ch^{\pm}({\cal C})$ be the category of sequences of pairs of morphisms in ${\cal C}$, called parity quasicomplexes (PQC) [PQC]:
Definition 8 Mapping $\phi:T^{*}M\to T^{*}N$ is observable in $LS$ if functions $\overline{\pi}\circ\phi$ and $L_{h}\overline{\pi}\circ\phi$ are observable in $LS$.
Definition 4 A mapping $\Psi:M\times U\to N\times V$ is called a morphism of Lagrangian systems from $LS$ to $LS^{\prime}$ if it maps solutions of $LS$ into solutions of $LS^{\prime}$.
Definition 6 A Lagrangian system $LS$ is called non-degenerate if it satisfies the following conditions: 1. A system of nonlinear algebraic eqations $\partial{\cal H}/\partial{u^{k}}=0,k=\overline{1,m}$ can be resolved with respect to $u$, the soluition $\hat{u}=\hat{h}(p,q)$ is unique and the mapping $\hat{u}:T^{*}M\to U$ is smooth. 2. The matrix $f_{u}$ has full rank: $rank\biggl{[}\frac{\partial{f^{i}}}{\partial{u^{k}}}\biggr{]}=m,$ where $i=\overline{1,n}$ and $k=\overline{1,m}$.
Definition 2 A Lagrangian system $LS$ is a triplet $(M,CDS,L)$, where $M$ is a manifold, $dimM=n$, $CDS$ is a controllable dynamic system on $M$, and $L$ is a function $M\times U\to R$.
Definition 1 Mapping $\phi:M\to N$ is called a morphism of Hamiltonian systems if for any solution $z(t),t\in[0,T]$ of the system $HS$ its image under the mapping $\phi$ is a solution of the system $HS^{\prime}$ on the interval $t\in[0,T]$.
Definition 9 A point $(q_{0},u_{0})\in M\times U$ is called a regular point of $LS$ if the set $R=\overline{\pi}^{-1}(q_{0})\times ker_{u_{0}}\Delta$ (in coordinates: $R=\{(p,q)\in T^{*}M:q=q_{0},u_{0}=\hat{u}(p,q_{0})\}$) does not contain singular points of $HS$ and the rank of the set of the functions $L_{h}^{s}q^{i},i=\overline{0,n},s=0,1,\dots$ is constant in the vicinity of each point in $R$.
Definition 5 A function ${\cal H}(p,q,u)=p_{i}f^{i}(q,u)-L(q,u)$ defined on $(T^{*}M)\times U$ is called Pontryagin function of the Lagrangian system $LS=(M,CDS,L)$.
Definition 3 A solution $\gamma(t)=(q(t),u(t))$ of Lagrangian system $LS=(M,CDS,L)$ is a curve providing a local extremum to the functional ${\cal L}$ on the class of admissible curves with fixed boundary points.
Definition 7 A function $S:T^{*}M\to R$ is called observable in $LS$ if there exists a function $\Psi:M\times U\to R$ such that the following diagram commutes $T^{*}M$$M\times U$$R$$\Delta$$S$$\Psi$ where $\Delta=\pi\times\hat{u}$ is morphism of fiber bundles $\pi:T^{*}M\to M$ and $\pi^{\prime}:M\times U\to M$.
Definition 2.2. We say that $\mathcal{A}$ is a functorial retract of $\mathcal{B}$, if the projection functor from $\operatorname{Retr}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ to $\mathcal{A}$ has a right inverse. We shall call such an inverse a functorial retraction of $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathbf{F}$ be a functor from a category $\mathcal{A}$ to a category $\mathcal{B}$, let $A\in\operatorname{Ob}\mathcal{A}$, $B\in\operatorname{Ob}\mathcal{B}$, and $\varphi\colon\mathbf{F}(A)\to B$. A projectability witness for $\left\langle{\varphi,A,B}\right\rangle$ (with respect to $\mathbf{F}$) is a pair $\left\langle{a,\varepsilon}\right\rangle$ satisfying the following conditions: (i) $a\colon A\twoheadrightarrow\,\overline{\!A}$ is an epic in $\mathcal{A}$. (ii) $\varepsilon\colon\mathbf{F}(\,\overline{\!A})\to B$ is an isomorphism in $\mathcal{B}$. (iii) $\varphi=\varepsilon\circ\mathbf{F}(a)$. (iv) For every $f\colon A\to X$ in $\mathcal{A}$ and every $\eta\colon\mathbf{F}(\,\overline{\!A})\to\mathbf{F}(X)$ such that $\mathbf{F}(f)=\eta\circ\mathbf{F}(a)$, there exists $g\colon\,\overline{\!A}\to X$ in $\mathcal{A}$ such that $f=g\circ a$ and $\eta=\mathbf{F}(g)$. We say that $\mathbf{F}$ is projectable, if every triple $\left\langle{\varphi,A,B}\right\rangle$, where $\varphi\colon\mathbf{F}(A)\to B$ is a projection, has a projectability witness.
Definition 3.1. In a category $\mathcal{C}$, a morphism $f\colon A\to B$ is a projection, if there exists a decomposition of the form $A=B\mathbin{\Pi}B^{\prime}$ (wrt. $f$, $f^{\prime}$) in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be subcategories of a category $\mathcal{C}$. We denote by $\operatorname{Retr}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ the category whose objects and morphisms are the following: — Objects: all quadruples $\left\langle{A,B,\varepsilon,\mu}\right\rangle$, where $A\in\operatorname{Ob}\mathcal{A}$, $B\in\operatorname{Ob}\mathcal{B}$, $\varepsilon\colon A\to\nobreak B$, $\mu\colon B\to A$, and $\mu\circ\varepsilon=\mathrm{id}_{A}$. — Morphisms: a morphism from $\left\langle{A,B,\varepsilon,\mu}\right\rangle$ to $\left\langle{A^{\prime},B^{\prime},\varepsilon^{\prime},\mu^{\prime}}\right\rangle$ is a pair $\left\langle{f,g}\right\rangle$, where $f\colon A\to A^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{A}$, $g\colon B\to B^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{B}$, $g\circ\varepsilon=\varepsilon^{\prime}\circ f$, and $\mu^{\prime}\circ g=f\circ\mu$. Composition of morphisms is defined by the rule $\left\langle{f^{\prime},g^{\prime}}\right\rangle\circ\left\langle{f,g}\right% \rangle=\left\langle{f^{\prime}\circ f,g^{\prime}\circ g}\right\rangle$. The projection functor from $\operatorname{Retr}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ to $\mathcal{A}$ is the functor from $\operatorname{Retr}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ to $\mathcal{A}$ that sends any object $\left\langle{A,B,\varepsilon,\mu}\right\rangle$ to $A$ and any morphism $\left\langle{f,g}\right\rangle$ to $f$.
Definition 2.2 ${\mathbb{N}}(G,H,R)$ is the ${\mathbb{N}}(H,R)$-linear finitely semi-simple strict 2-category of which the simple objects are precisely the elements of $G$, and for which the ${\mathbb{N}}(H,R)$-module category of endomorphisms on $g\in G$ is defined by $\hbox{End}(g)={\mathbb{N}}(H,R)$.
Definition 3.2 We say that two semi-weak monoidal 2-category structures on ${\mathbb{N}}(G,H,R)$, as defined in Def. 3.1, are 2-equivalent if there exist 1. Automorphisms $G\to G$, $H\to H$, and $R\to R$, which we denote by $g\mapsto\overline{g}$, $h\mapsto\overline{h}$, and $r\mapsto\overline{r}$. The first two automorphisms are required to be group automorphisms, the third one is required to be a unital ring automorphism which preserves the involution. 2. A map $\mu\colon H\times H\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\mu_{h_{1},h_{2}}\colon\overline{h_{1}h_{2}}\Rightarrow\overline{h}_{1}% \overline{h}_{2}$. 3. A map $\Phi\colon G\times G\to H$, which corresponds to a family of simple invertible 1-morphisms $\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}\colon\overline{g_{1}g_{2}}\to\overline{g}_{1}\overline{g}_{2}$. 4. A map $\phi\colon G\times G\times G\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}\overline{g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3}}}>{}>\overline% {g}_{1}(\overline{g_{2}g_{3}})@>{\Phi_{g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>\overline{g}_{1}(% \overline{g}_{2}\overline{g}_{3})\\ @V{\overline{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}}V{}V\Big{\Uparrow}\phi_{g_{1},g_{% 2},g_{3}}@V{}V{(\alpha^{0})^{\prime}_{\overline{g}_{1},\overline{g}_{2},% \overline{g}_{3}}}V\\ \overline{(g_{1}g_{2})g_{3}}@>{\Phi_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(\overline{g_{1}g_{% 2}})\overline{g}_{3}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}}>{}>(\overline{g}_{1}\overline{g}_{2% })\overline{g}_{3}\end{CD}$ 5. A map $\psi\colon H\times G\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}\overline{g_{1}g_{2}}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}}>{}>\overline{g}_{1}% \overline{g}_{2}\\ @V{\overline{h}_{1}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\psi_{h_{1},g_{2}}@V{}V{\overline{h}_{% 1}}V\\ \overline{g_{1}g_{2}}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}}>{}>\overline{g}_{1}\overline{g}_{2% }\end{CD}$ 6. A map $\chi\colon G\times H\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}\overline{g_{1}g_{2}}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}}>{}>\overline{g}_{1}% \overline{g}_{2}\\ @V{\overline{h}_{2}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\chi_{g_{1},h_{2}}@V{}V{\overline{h}_{% 2}}V\\ \overline{g_{1}g_{2}}@>{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}}}>{}>\overline{g}_{1}\overline{g}_{2% }\end{CD}$ All these maps are required to be normalized. Furthermore, they should satisfy 1. $\overline{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}\Phi_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3}}\Phi_{g_{1},g_% {2}}=\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3}}\Phi_{g_{2},g_{3}}(\alpha^{0})^{\prime}_{\overline% {g}_{1},\overline{g}_{2},\overline{g}_{3}}.$ 2. $\overline{\alpha^{1}_{h_{1},h_{2},h_{3}}}\mu_{h_{1}h_{2},h_{3}}\mu_{h_{1},h_{2% }}=\mu_{h_{1},h_{2}h_{3}}\mu_{h_{2},h_{3}}(\alpha^{1})^{\prime}_{\overline{h}_% {1},\overline{h}_{2},\overline{h}_{3}}.$ From now on we do not write $\alpha^{1}$, $(\alpha^{1})^{\prime}$, or $\mu$ any longer. As explained in Def. 3.1, we use the brackets $\lceil\rceil$, which “absorb” these three maps. 3. $\lceil\overline{\tau_{h_{1},h_{2}}}\rceil=\lceil\tau^{\prime}_{\overline{h}_{1% },\overline{h}_{2}}\rceil.$ 4. $\lceil\psi_{h,g_{2}}\rceil\lceil\psi_{h,g_{3}}\rceil\lceil\overline{\iota^{1}_% {h,g_{2},g_{3}}}\rceil=\lceil(\iota^{1})^{\prime}_{\overline{h},\overline{g}_{% 2},\overline{g}_{3}}\lceil(\tau^{\prime})^{-1}_{\overline{h},\Phi_{g_{2},g_{3}% }}\rceil\lceil\psi_{h,g_{2}g_{3}}\rceil.$ 5. $\lceil\overline{\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h,g_{3}}}\rceil=\lceil(\iota^{2})^{\prime}_{% \overline{g}_{1},\overline{h},\overline{g}_{3}}\rceil.$ 6. $\lceil\tau^{\prime}_{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}},\overline{h}}\rceil\lceil\chi_{g_{1}g_% {2},h}\rceil\lceil\overline{\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h}}\rceil=\lceil(\iota^{3})% ^{\prime}_{\overline{g}_{1},\overline{g}_{2},\overline{h}}\rceil\lceil\chi_{g_% {2},h}\rceil\lceil\chi_{g_{1},h}\rceil.$ 7. $\lceil\psi_{h_{1}h_{2},g}\rceil=\lceil\psi_{h_{1},g}\rceil\lceil\psi_{h_{2},g}\rceil.$ 8. $\lceil\chi_{g,h_{1}h_{2}}\rceil=\lceil\chi_{g,h_{1}}\rceil\lceil\chi_{g,h_{2}}\rceil.$ 9. $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\lceil\psi^{-1}_{\overline{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},% g_{3}}},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil\phi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}\rceil\lceil\phi_{g_{1},g_{2% }g_{3},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil(\iota^{2})^{\prime}_{\overline{g}_{1},\Phi_{g_{2},g_% {3}},\overline{g}_{4}}\rceil\\ &\displaystyle\times\lceil\chi^{-1}_{g_{1},\alpha^{0}_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}}% \rceil\lceil\phi_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil\pi^{\prime}_{\overline{g}_{1}% ,\overline{g}_{2},\overline{g}_{3},\overline{g}_{4}}\rceil\\ \displaystyle=&\displaystyle\lceil\overline{\pi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}}% \rceil\lceil\phi_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil(\iota^{1})^{\prime}_{% \Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}},\overline{g}_{3},\overline{g}_{4}}\rceil\lceil(\tau^{\prime% })^{-1}_{\Phi_{g_{1},g_{2}},\Phi_{g_{3},g_{4}}}\rceil\\ &\displaystyle\times\lceil\phi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}g_{4}}\rceil\lceil(\iota^{3})% ^{\prime}_{\overline{g}_{1},\overline{g}_{2},\Phi_{g_{3},g_{4}}}\rceil.\end{split}$
Definition 4.2 $Z(M,{\cal T})=(\#G)^{-v_{0}}(\#H)^{(v_{0}-v_{1})}\sum_{\ell}\prod_{S}Z(S,\ell)% ^{\epsilon(S)}.$
Definition 3.1 A semi-weak monoidal 2-category structure on ${\mathbb{N}}(G,H,R)$ consists of the following maps: 0-associator $\alpha^{0}\colon G\times G\times G\to H$, which corresponds to a family of simple invertible 1-morphisms $\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}\colon g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})\to(g_{1}g_{2})g_{3}$. pentagonator $\pi\colon G\times G\times G\times G\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}g_{1}(g_{2}(g_{3}g_{4}))@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}g_{4}}}>{}>(% g_{1}g_{2})(g_{3}g_{4})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}}>{}>((g_{1}g_{2}% )g_{3})g_{4}\\ @V{\alpha^{0}_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\pi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3},g% _{4}}@A{}A{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}A\\ g_{1}((g_{2}g_{3})g_{4})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3},g_{4}}}>{}>(g_{1}(g_{2% }g_{3}))g_{4}\end{CD}$ 1-associator $\alpha^{1}\colon H\times H\times H\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\alpha^{1}_{h_{1},h_{2},h_{3}}\colon h_{1}(h_{2}h_{3})\Rightarrow(h_{1}h_{2})h% _{3}$. tensorator $\tau\colon H\times H\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}g_{1}g_{2}@>{h_{1}}>{}>g_{1}g_{2}\\ @V{h_{2}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\tau_{h_{1},h_{2}}@V{}V{h_{2}}V\\ g_{1}g_{2}@>{h_{1}}>{}>g_{1}g_{2}\end{CD}$ interchanger1 $\iota^{1}\colon H\times G\times G\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g% _{3}\\ @V{h_{1}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\iota^{1}_{h_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}@V{}V{h_{1}}V\\ g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g_{3}\end{CD}$ interchanger2 $\iota^{2}\colon G\times H\times G\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g% _{3}\\ @V{h_{2}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h_{2},g_{3}}@V{}V{h_{2}}V\\ g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g_{3}\end{CD}$ interchanger3 $\iota^{3}\colon G\times G\times H\to R^{*}$, which corresponds to a family of invertible 2-morphisms $\begin{CD}g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g% _{3}\\ @V{h_{3}}V{}V\Big{\Downarrow}\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h_{3}}@V{}V{h_{3}}V\\ g_{1}(g_{2}g_{3})@>{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}}>{}>(g_{1}g_{2})g_{3}\end{CD}$ All these maps are required to be normalized, i.e., their value is equal to $1$ whenever one of the factors of their argument is equal to $1$. Furthermore these maps are required to satisfy the following identities: $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\alpha^{0}_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}(\alpha^{0}_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}})^{-1}\alpha% ^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3},g_{4}}(\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}g_{4}})^{-1}\alpha^% {0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}=1.$ $(\rightarrow\rightarrow\rightarrow\rightarrow)$ $\alpha^{1}_{h_{2},h_{3},h_{4}}(\alpha^{1}_{h_{1}h_{2},h_{3},h_{4}})^{-1}\alpha% ^{1}_{h_{1},h_{2}h_{3},h_{4}}(\alpha^{1}_{h_{1},h_{2},h_{3}h_{4}})^{-1}\alpha^% {1}_{h_{1},h_{2},h_{3}}=1.$ In the following identities we avoid writing $\alpha^{1}$ constantly and bracket the remaining maps with $\lceil\rceil$ following Crane and Yetter’s [26] notation. As explained in [26] this notation means that the source and target 1-morphisms are assumed to be parenthesized from left to right. The brackets denote the strings of 1-associators that are required to make the 2-morphisms composable under this assumption. The usage of these brackets is unambiguous by the coherence relation of the 1-associator, which corresponds to $(\rightarrow\rightarrow\rightarrow\rightarrow)$. $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\tau_{h_{1}h_{2},h_{3}}\rceil=\lceil\tau_{h_{2},h_{3}}\rceil\lceil\tau_{% h_{1},h_{3}}\rceil,$ and $\lceil\tau_{h_{1},h_{2}h_{3}}\rceil=\lceil\tau_{h_{1},h_{2}}\rceil\lceil\tau_{% h_{1},h_{3}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\pi_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4},g_{5}}\rceil\lceil\pi_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3},g_{4},g_{% 5}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{1}_{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}};g_{4};g_{5}}\rceil% \lceil\pi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}g_{5}}\rceil=$ $\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1};\alpha^{0}_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}};g_{5}}\rceil\lceil\pi_{g% _{1},g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil\pi_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}g_{4},g_{5}}\rceil% \lceil(\iota^{3}_{g_{1};g_{2};\alpha^{0}_{g_{3},g_{4},g_{5}}})^{-1}\rceil% \lceil\pi_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3},g_{4},g_{5}}\rceil.$ $(\rightarrow\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\iota^{1}_{h,g_{2},g_{3}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{1}_{h,g_{2}g_{3},g_{4}}% \rceil\lceil\tau^{-1}_{h;\alpha^{0}_{g_{2},g_{3},g_{4}}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{1}% _{h,g_{3},g_{4}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{1}_{h,g_{2},g_{3}g_{4}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\rightarrow\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h,g_{3}g_{4}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h,g_{3}}% \rceil\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h,g_{4}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\rightarrow\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1}g_{2},h,g_{4}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h,g_{4}}% \rceil\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{2},h,g_{4}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\rightarrow)$ $\lceil\tau_{\alpha^{0}_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}};h}\rceil\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2% }g_{3},h}\rceil\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{2},g_{3},h}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1}g_{% 2},g_{3},h}\rceil\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h}\rceil.$ $(\rightarrow\rightarrow\otimes\bullet\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\iota^{1}_{h_{1}h_{2},g_{2},g_{3}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{1}_{h_{1},g_{2},g_% {3}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{1}_{h_{2},g_{2},g_{3}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\rightarrow\rightarrow\otimes\bullet)$ $\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h_{1}h_{2},g_{3}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h_{1},g_% {3}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{1},h_{2},g_{3}}\rceil.$ $(\bullet\otimes\bullet\otimes\rightarrow\rightarrow)$ $\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h_{1}h_{2}}\rceil=\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h_% {1}}\rceil\lceil\iota^{3}_{g_{1},g_{2},h_{2}}\rceil.$
Definition 2.1 ${\mathbb{N}}(H,R)$ is the $R$-linear finitely semi-simple category with the simple objects being precisely the elements of $H$, and for which the $R$-module of endomorphisms of an object $h\in H$ is defined by $\hbox{End}(h)=R$. The composite of two such endomorphisms, $r_{1}$ and $r_{2}$, is defined by their product $r_{1}r_{2}$ in $R$.
Definition 4.1 $\begin{split}\displaystyle Z((ijklm))=&\displaystyle\lceil(\iota^{3}_{g_{lm},g% _{kl},h_{ijk}})^{-1}\rceil\lceil\tau_{h_{klm},h_{ijk}}\rceil\lceil(\iota^{1}_{% h_{klm},g_{jk},g_{ij}})^{-1}\rceil\\ &\displaystyle\times\lceil\iota^{2}_{g_{lm},h_{jkl},g_{ij}}\rceil\lceil\pi_{g_% {lm},g_{kl},g_{jk},g_{ij}}\rceil.\end{split}$
Definition 3.1 A corepresentation of $(A,\Delta)$ on $B$ is an element $V\in M(A\otimes B)$ such that $(\Delta\otimes\iota)V=V_{13}V_{23}$.
Definition 5.2 Let $B$ be a $*$-algebra and ${\cal K}$ a $*$-category. Then the category $\mathrm{Rep}_{\cal K}\,B$ of ‘representations of $B$ in ${\cal K}$’ has as objects the pairs $(X,\pi_{X})$, where $X\in\mathrm{Obj}\,{\cal K}$ and $\pi_{X}$ is a non-degenerate $*$-homomorphism of $B$ into $\mathrm{End}\,X$. The morphisms are given by $\mathrm{Mor}_{\mathrm{Rep}_{\cal K}B}((X,\pi_{X}),(Y,\pi_{Y}))=\{s\in\mathrm{% Mor}_{\cal K}(X,Y)\ |\ s\,\circ\,\pi_{X}(b)=\pi_{Y}(b)\,\circ\,s\ \ \forall b% \in B\}.$
Definition 5.27 Let ${\cal C},{\cal D}$ be strict tensor categories and $E,E^{\prime}:{\cal C}\rightarrow{\cal D}$ be tensor functors (with structural isomorphisms $e,e^{\prime},d_{X,Y},d^{\prime}_{X,Y}$). Then $E,E^{\prime}$ are said to be isomorphic as tensor functors, $E\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\otimes}}{{\cong}}E^{\prime}$, if the diagram $\diagram E(X)\otimes E(Y)&\rTo^{u_{X}\otimes u_{Y}}&E^{\prime}(X)\otimes E^{% \prime}(Y)\\ \dTo_{d_{X,Y}}&&\dTo^{d^{\prime}_{X,Y}}\\ E(X\otimes Y)&\rTo_{u_{X\otimes Y}}&E^{\prime}(X\otimes Y)$ commutes for all $X,Y\in{\cal C}$, where $u:E\rightarrow E^{\prime}$ is a natural transformation whose components $u_{X}:E(X)\rightarrow E^{\prime}(X)$ are isomorphisms. A similar and obvious commutative diagram involves the structural isomorphisms $e,e^{\prime}$. If ${\cal C},{\cal D}$ are tensor $*$-categories and $E,E^{\prime}$ are $*$-preserving then all $u_{X}$ must be unitary.
